─── STEP 5: WHEN TO USE ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    - Codec/driver/plugin systems where type is selected at runtime from a string.
    - Any place where new types may be registered without changing calling code.
    - Parsers: select the right parser based on file extension or MIME type.
    - Network protocol handlers: select handler based on message type field.
    - Deserializers: select concrete type from a discriminator field in data.

─── STEP 6: WHEN NOT TO USE ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    - When the type is always known at compile time — just construct directly.
    - When there is only one possible type — adds indirection with no benefit.
    - When construction logic is trivial — just write make_unique<T>().

─── STEP 7: COMMON MISTAKES ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    - Returning a raw pointer instead of unique_ptr — ownership is unclear.
    - Not registering types at program start — getting runtime errors instead of compile errors.
    - Calling creator functions under a write lock when they are slow — holds the lock too long.
    - Forgetting that std::function has overhead — for extreme hot paths, use a function pointer table.

